ounts are prepared.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>4. The Department ceased to collect data via the annual Financial Returns for NHS trusts from 2012-13 onwards. Data has therefore only been provided for 2010-11 and 2011-12.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter","206981","2014-09-03T14:00:57.5141913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79387/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79387/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79387/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust has spent on permanent nursing staff in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","206982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79388","Department of Health","false","2014-09-04","<p>Reports of ‘suspected’ adverse drug reactions (ADRs) are collected by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) and Commission for Human Medicines through the spontaneous reporting scheme; the Yellow Card Scheme. The scheme collects ADR reports from across the whole United Kingdom and includes all medicines, including those from prescriptions, over-the-counter or general retail sales. Reports are also received for herbal medicines and other unlicensed medicines.</p><p>There is unknown and a variable level of under-reporting to the Yellow Card Scheme meaning that data collected cannot be used to calculate incidence, as such we cannot provide the number of serious health events per thousand. We are unable to calculate this incidence because neither the total number of reactions occurring in the population, nor the number of patients using the drug is known.</p><p>The following table shows the total number of serious UK spontaneous ‘suspected’ ADR reports received by the MHRA between 23 July 2013 and 22 July 2014 broken down for E-Cigarettes, Nicotine Replacement Therapies (excluding E-Cigarettes) and Varenicline:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Total Serious Reports</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Varenicline</p></td><td><p>297</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nicotine Replacement therapy</p></td><td><p>75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>E-Cigarettes</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-09-04T13:15:22.548935Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79388/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79388/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79388/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many serious health events have been recorded per thousand (a) e-cigarette users, (b) users of nicotine replacement therapies and (c) users of the Champix form of varenicline in the last year.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","206979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79389","Department of Health","false","2014-09-05","<p> </p><p>University College Hospitals London (UCHL) did not apply to be a contracted provider of gamma knife services for NHS England. For this reason it has not been formally assessed against the service specification. The gamma knife referred to is owned and operated by Queen’s Square Radiotherapy Centre (QSRC) Ltd, a private company wholly owned by Medical Equipment Solutions Limited, in premises owned by UCLH under a commercial agreement with UCLH.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As the National Health Service was going through a major transition in 2013-14 it was decided at that time that there should be no new market entrants for stereotactic radiotherapy services. Therefore only existing commissioned providers were asked to identify the services that they considered themselves to be providing, and UCLH did not express an interest in respect to gamma knife treatment. QSRC Ltd is not an existing NHS England commissioned provider and therefore was not assessed against the service specification.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All patients need to be treated in accordance with the prescribed clinical pathways and in line with contractual agreements with providers. If providers treat outside the required contractual agreements then they do so at their own financial risk, and this is why NHS England instructs hospitals to this effect where no contractual arrangement is in place.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","206965","2014-09-05T13:32:07.7570988Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79389/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79389/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79389/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Radiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will investigate the reasons why NHS England is instructing hospitals with patients presenting as clinically urgent to treat such patients with innovative radiotherapy at the hospital's financial risk while it decides whether to fund the patient; and if he will issue guidelines on how hospitals which have followed that instruction will receive reimbursement for such expenditure if NHS England subsequently refuses to fund the treatment.","false","Biography information for Tessa Munt","Wells","Tessa Munt","206974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79390","Department of Health","false","2014-09-03","<p> </p><p>In its Fiscal Sustainability Reports – the latest of which was published on 10 July 2014 – the Office for Budget Responsibility publishes estimates of long-term public spending, including health care, up to 2063-64. These estimates incorporate a number of assumptions, including the impact of expected demographic change.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-09-03T14:33:12.4449673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79390/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79390/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79390/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Health Services: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 17 July 2014, Official Report, columns 766-7W on NHS: funding, if he will estimate the cost of the challenge posed by the pressures posed by the pressures of an aging population and the cost of new investment.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","206873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79391","Department of Health","false","2014-09-03","<p> </p><p>A table has been placed in the Library which sets out the number of dental contracts reported to the NHS Business Services Authority as in place between 1 April 2013 and 31 March 2014, the name of the contract holder and the area in which the contract is held. The table includes start and, where applicable, finish dates. It also shows the contract value, commissioned and completed units of dental activity and units of orthodontic activity.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter","206851","2014-09-03T13:54:20.0102146Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79391/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79391/answer","PQ206851_876 - Lib Doc - Table.xlsx","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79391/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what area is covered by each NHS dentistry contract commissioned between 1 April 2013 and 31 March 2014; what the start and finish dates are of each contract area; what the value of each contract is; and how many units of dental activity were (a) contracted to be completed and (b) completed between 1 April 2013 and 31 March 2014 under each contract.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","206876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79392","Department of Health","false","2014-09-02","<p>The Department has not made a specific assessment of the potential of the Men’s Sheds movement. The Department welcomes the positive impact that community based schemes like this can have in helping to combat loneliness and isolation. The effect that loneliness and isolation have on health and wellbeing is an important factor in government policy.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-09-02T14:37:50.5827849Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79392/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79392/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79392/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Health: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential of the Men's Sheds movement to have a positive impact on health and wellbeing.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","206875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79393","Department of Health","false","2014-09-03","<p> </p><p>Prior to the establishment of the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) in April 2006, the main part of the Department's total health research expenditure was devolved to and managed by national health service organisations. From April 2006 to March 2009, transitional research funding was allocated to these organisations at reducing levels. The organisations have accounted for their use of the allocations they have received from the Department in an annual research and development report. The reports identify total, aggregated expenditure on national priority areas but do not provide details of spend on research into specific diseases including motor neurone disease (MND).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Expenditure on MND research by the NIHR from 2009-10 through research programmes, research centres and units, and research fellowships is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>£ million</em></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>0.1</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td><td><p>0.4</p></td><td><p>0.7</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Total spend by the NIHR on MND research is higher than this because expenditure by the NIHR Clinical Research Network (CRN) on this topic cannot be disaggregated from total CRN expenditure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health (Jeremy Hunt) has had no discussions on funding for MND research with the Scottish Government Cabinet Secretary for Health and Wellbeing.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter","206931","2014-09-03T14:35:42.8449035Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79393/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79393/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79393/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Motor Neurone Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much funding his Department has allocated to research into motor neurone disease in each of last 10 years.","false","Biography information for John Robertson","Glasgow North West","John Robertson","206942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79394","Department of Health","false","2014-09-02","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-09-02T14:40:23.8577231Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79394/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79394/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79394/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Mental Health Services: Out of Area Treatment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people referred for mental health care received out-of-area treatment from Mid Yorkshire Hospitals trust; and how many such people were (a) children and (b) adults.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","206938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79395","Department of Health","false","2014-09-05","<p> </p><p>The Department collects information on expenditure with private sector providers but not to which providers local contracts have been awarded.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2013-14, commissioners’ spending on healthcare from private sector providers equated to approximately 6% of total National Health Service expenditure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Whether services are provided by the public, voluntary or private sector, they remain publicly funded and free at the point of delivery with access based on clinical need.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is for local commissioners to decide how best to secure local services and take decisions on which is the most capable provider to deliver those services in the best interests of their patients. There is no requirement for commissioners to put all services to competitive tender.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-09-05T14:23:08.2941675Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79395/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79395/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Health Services: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what health services have been privatised in Mid Yorkshire in the last 12 months; and what the cost was of tendering those services.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","206939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79396","Department of Health","false","2014-09-05","<p> </p><p>Ambulance services in Yorkshire are provided by the Yorkshire Ambulance Service NHS Trust.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England only regularly collect median average ambulance response times from entire ambulance trusts. It is not possible to give such figures for smaller areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The median averages for the Yorkshire Ambulance Service for the last 12 months for which data is available are in the following table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Table: The median ambulance response times to treatment for category A<sup>1</sup> calls for Yorkshire Ambulance Service NHS Trust, April 2011 to April 2014 inclusive</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Month</p></td><td><p>Median time to treatment for<br> Category A calls (in minutes)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2013</p></td><td><p>5.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2013</p></td><td><p>5.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2013</p></td><td><p>5.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2013</p></td><td><p>5.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2013</p></td><td><p>5.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2013</p></td><td><p>5.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November 2013</p></td><td><p>5.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2013</p></td><td><p>5.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2014</p></td><td><p>5.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2014</p></td><td><p>5.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2014</p></td><td><p>5.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2014</p></td><td><p>6.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2014</p></td><td><p>6.9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Source</em>: Ambulance quality indicators, NHS England, www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ambulance-quality-indicators</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup>Category A calls are defined as those that are the result of immediately life threatening incidents.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-09-05T13:42:15.691499Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79396/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79396/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79396/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Ambulance Services: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average ambulance response time in the Mid Yorkshire NHS trust is.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","206940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79397","Department of Health","false","2014-09-03","<p> </p><p>All live births in England and Wales must be registered, regardless of gestational age. Data on live births by gestation are collected by the Office for National Statistics and published annually (as part of the statistical bulletin on gestation-specific infant mortality in England and Wales).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no current plans to establish a separate register of babies born before 24 weeks gestation.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-09-03T14:11:24.3439474Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79397/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79397/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-07-22","Babies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will establish a register of babies naturally born before 24 weeks gestation.","false","Biography information for Graeme Morrice","Livingston","Graeme Morrice","206929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79398","Department of Health","false","2014-09-03","<p> </p><p>Prior to the establishment of the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) in April 2006, the main part of the Department's total health research expenditure was devolved to and managed by national health service organisations. From April 2006 to March 2009, transitional research funding was allocated to these organisations at reducing levels. The organisations have accounted for their use of the allocations they have received from the Department in an annual research and development report. The reports identify total, aggregated expenditure on national priority areas but do not provide details of spend on research into specific diseases including motor neurone disease (MND).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Expenditure on MND research by the NIHR from 2009-10 through research programmes, research centres and units, and research fellowships is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>£ million</em></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>0.1</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td><td><p>0.4</p></td><td><p>0.7</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Total spend by the NIHR on MND research is higher than this because expenditure by the NIHR Clinical Research Network (CRN) on this topic cannot be disaggregated from total CRN expenditure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health (Jeremy Hunt) has had no discussions on funding for MND research with the Scottish Government Cabinet Secretary for Health and Wellbeing.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter","206942","2014-09-03T14:35:42.9073579Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79398/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79398/answer",,