"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79445","Scotland Office","false","2014-10-17","<p>The answer of 25 June 2014, Official Report, Column 208W, specified a total of £723,501 (plus VAT). This was fully inclusive of all costs incurred as part of the design, production and delivery process for <em>What Staying in the United Kingdom Means for Scotland</em>.</p><p> </p>","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael",,"2014-10-17T12:40:29.294588Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79445/answer","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79445/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-07-22","Sovereignty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, further to the Answer of 25 June 2014, Official Report, column 208W, on sovereignty, whether the figure provided in the Answer includes the cost of any amendments, alterations or destruction of any printed material promoting the Government's policy on the Scottish independence referendum.","false","Biography information for Stewart Hosie","Dundee East","Stewart Hosie","207050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79446","Scotland Office","false","2014-10-17","<p>The Scotland Office incurred no costs in amending, altering or destroying any leaflets promoting the Government’s policy on the Scottish independence referendum.</p><p> </p>","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael",,"2014-10-17T12:41:46.9682215Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79446/answer","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79446/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-07-22","Sovereignty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many leaflets produced by his Department promoting the Government's policy on the Scottish independence referendum have had to be amended, altered or destroyed; and at what cost to the public purse.","false","Biography information for Stewart Hosie","Dundee East","Stewart Hosie","207009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79447","Department for Transport","false","2014-09-02","<p> </p><p>The Highways Agency has an obligation to take account of ragwort and other injurious weeds growing on verges and other land for which it is responsible. In common with other landowners they are subject to the provisions of the Weeds Act 1959 as amended by the Ragwort Control Act 2003.</p><p> </p><p>On roadsides along the Strategic Road Network and other land under its control the Agency requires its service providers to follow the Defra Code of Practice to control ragwort. The code promotes a risk based approach with targeted use of control measures in locations close to land used either for animal grazing or fodder production. The principle measures used by the Agency are spot treatment with herbicide in spring and early summer followed by hand pulling of the weed later in the season.</p><p> </p><p><strong><strong></strong></strong></p><p /><p><strong><strong></strong></strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-09-02T15:08:20.9482461Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79447/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79447/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79447/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-07-22","Ragwort","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Highways Agency is taking to remove ragwort from (a) roadsides and (b) other land for which the Highways Agency is responsible.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","206869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79448","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-09-01","<p>No formal assessment of the effectiveness of the Men’s Sheds movement has been made to date.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-09-01T15:01:30.9332828Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79448/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79448/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-22","Employment: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Men's Sheds movement in building confidence and skills to help people back into work.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","206874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79449","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-09-01","<p /> <p /> <p>We have taken your question to refer to Personal Independence Payment. Statistics on clearance times for Personal Independence Payment are intended for future publication and the Department's analysts are currently considering what information will be included in the release.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-09-01T12:49:59.1999277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79449/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79449/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-22","Social Security Benefits: Terminal Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the average amount of time it takes for terminally ill people to receive a decision on their benefits claim.","false","Biography information for John Robertson","Glasgow North West","John Robertson","206941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79450","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-09-01","<p /> <p /> <p>I refer the Hon.Member to the written answer that the previous Minister for Disabled People gave on 14 July 2014, Official Report, column 589w, to the Hon. Member for East Lothian, Fiona O’Donnell.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Previous answer:</strong></p><p> </p><p>Fiona O'Donnell: To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions if he will classify motor neurone disease as a terminal illness which qualifies for a fast-track assessment for welfare claims. [204826]</p><p> </p><p>Mike Penning: Claims to attendance allowance, disability living allowance, employment and support allowance, incapacity benefit and personal independence payment from people who are terminally ill, as defined in law, are fast tracked. Claimants are considered to be terminally ill if they have a progressive disease as a result of which they are not expected to live longer than six months. Motor neurone disease is considered to be a progressive disease.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-09-01T15:35:34.8180349Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79450/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79450/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-22","Social Security Benefits: Terminal Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his policy is on fast-tracking benefits for terminally ill people.","false","Biography information for John Robertson","Glasgow North West","John Robertson","206932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79451","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-09-01","<p>DWP does not operate a blanket approach to compensation. Claimants who consider their assessment has been delayed by Atos or Capita should in the first instance take this up with the relevant company, who each have their own complaints process. If the complaint cannot be resolved, complainants will be signposted to DWP’s independent complaint tier, the Independent Case Examiner (ICE). If the ICE upholds the complaint, they will recommend redress for any impact on the complainant, in line with DWP policy on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/309964/financial-redress-maladministration-apr-14.pdf" target="_blank">Financial Redress for Maladministration</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","207007","2014-09-01T15:47:10.3948534Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79451/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79451/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-22","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to compensate people who wait more than a certain amount of time for assessments for personal independence payment or other benefits to be carried out by Atos or Capita.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79452","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-09-01","<p>DWP does not operate a blanket approach to compensation. Claimants who consider their assessment has been delayed by Atos or Capita should in the first instance take this up with the relevant company, who each have their own complaints process. If the complaint cannot be resolved, complainants will be signposted to DWP’s independent complaint tier, the Independent Case Examiner (ICE). If the ICE upholds the complaint, they will recommend redress for any impact on the complainant, in line with DWP policy on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/309964/financial-redress-maladministration-apr-14.pdf" target="_blank">Financial Redress for Maladministration</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","207006","2014-09-01T15:47:10.4613093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79452/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79452/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-22","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to compensate people whose assessment appointments for personal independence payment or other benefits are cancelled more than a certain number of times by Atos or Capita.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79453","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-09-01","<p /> <p /> <p>The Department operates a discretionary special payment scheme. The policy and guiding principles of the scheme are described in <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/309964/financial-redress-maladministration-apr-14.pdf" target="_blank">Financial Redress for Maladministration</a> which is available on Gov.UK.</p><p> </p><p>Employment and Support Allowance claimants will normally be in receipt of benefit while they wait for their assessment and any arrears due are paid once a decision is made.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>By the autumn, we expect no one to be waiting for a Personal Independence Payment assessment for longer than 26 weeks. By the end of the year, we expect no one will be waiting longer than 16 weeks.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Any delays experienced in the Personal Independence Payment new claims process will not affect the date from which claimants are paid – all successful claims will be paid from the date the claim was initially made.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-09-01T16:57:23.1530159Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79453/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79453/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-22","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria he uses to decide whether people who have to wait more than a certain time for the medical assessment for access to benefits should be eligible for compensation.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","207004"
