"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79102","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-09-10","<p /> <p>The Ministry of Justice discussed the Social Action, Responsibility and Heroism Bill with officials from the Health and Safety Executive and senior members of the judiciary prior to its introduction. There have been no discussions with the insurance industry regarding the Bill. There is nothing in the Bill which prevents an employee bringing a negligence claim, or which leaves workers without appropriate remedies when they are injured by the negligent actions of irresponsible employers. We do not therefore expect it to lead to workers taking out personal insurance cover.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","206699 ; 206706 ; 206712","2014-09-10T15:17:41.1757184Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79102/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79102/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-21","Social Action, Responsibility and Heroism Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he has had with the judiciary on the need for the Social Action, Responsibility and Heroism Bill.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Mr Andy Slaughter","206713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79103","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-09-10","<p /> <p>The Ministry of Justice discussed the Social Action, Responsibility and Heroism Bill with officials from the Health and Safety Executive and senior members of the judiciary prior to its introduction. There have been no discussions with the insurance industry regarding the Bill. There is nothing in the Bill which prevents an employee bringing a negligence claim, or which leaves workers without appropriate remedies when they are injured by the negligent actions of irresponsible employers. We do not therefore expect it to lead to workers taking out personal insurance cover.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","206706 ; 206712 ; 206713","2014-09-10T15:17:40.8755869Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79103/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79103/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-21","Social Action, Responsibility and Heroism Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions his Department had with the Health and Safety Executive before the introduction of the Social Action, Responsibility and Heroism Bill.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Mr Andy Slaughter","206699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79104","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-09-12","<p> </p><p>The primary function of the civil courts is to provide a forum in which private individuals can resolve their disputes. It is for the creditor to pursue enforcement of any costs order in his or her favour in another jurisdiction. The success of enforcement abroad largely depends on the nature of the order and where it is to be enforced, since the recognition and enforcement of judgments of a foreign jurisdiction will depend on the private international law rules (including any rules applicable due to international agreements) of the state in which it is sought to enforce.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-09-12T13:09:19.8470992Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79104/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79104/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-21","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he plans to take to enforce the payment of costs awarded against off-shore hedge funds by the courts in civil cases decided in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Bob Ainsworth","Coventry North East","Mr Bob Ainsworth","206701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79105","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-09-10","<p> </p><p>The Hallett Review drew attention to issues regarding record-keeping about the RPM, which the Northern Ireland Office is addressing. The Hallett Review did not deal with the exercise of the RPM prior to 1997 but only touches upon it in passing. During the pre-1998 period the use of RPM was relatively common: it was not recorded centrally and records are likely to have been destroyed in accordance with proper protocols. Where the RPM was used prior to 1997 to remit (i.e. shorten) the sentences of individuals who had already been convicted of offences, their release from custody can, on occasion, provide some evidence of the exercise of the RPM. In addition, there may in some cases, be contemporaneous correspondence which provides evidence of the exercise of the RPM.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-09-10T14:56:21.782779Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79105/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79105/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-07-21","Administrative Scheme for the "On the Runs" Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, with reference to the report of the Hallett Review, how in the absence of the lost records a beneficiary of the Royal Prerogative of Mercy prior to 1997 is able to demonstrate the grant of the exercise of the Royal Prerogative; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","206670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79106","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-09-04","<p> </p><p>The decision whether or not to prosecute an individual is a matter for the independent prosecuting authorities.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-09-04T11:34:58.3234965Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79106/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79106/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-07-21","Administrative Scheme for the "On the Runs" Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, with reference to paragraph 2.58 of the report of the Hallett Review, whether the individual x has been prosecuted; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","206671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79107","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-09-01","<p> </p><p>My Department has accommodation at three locations:-</p><p>1 Horse Guards Road, London, Hillsborough Castle (Co. Down), and Stormont House, Belfast.</p><p>The London office relocated from 11 Millbank to 1 Horse Guards Road in February 2013. This move enabled the Department to secure significant savings of just under £1m per annum. In July 2014, the Northern Ireland Office’s (NIO) footprint within 1 Horse Guards was further reduced which will create an additional annual saving of approximately £58,000.</p><p>On 1 April 2014, my Department transferred responsibility for the management and day to day running of Hillsborough Castle, whilst retaining accommodation and an office for Ministers, to the charity Historic Royal Palaces. This new arrangement will achieve significant savings for the NIO, with the added benefit of enabling the Castle to become fully open to the people of Northern Ireland and visitors from abroad.</p><p>My Department will continue to keep under review potential options to make further savings at all three of its locations.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-09-01T15:08:20.7645896Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79107/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79107/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-07-21","Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if she will review her departmental estate in order to reduce costs; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","206693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79108","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-09-01","<p>We have been clear that Israel has a right to defend itself. The UN Human Rights Council has set up a Commission of Inquiry to investigate purported violations of international humanitarian and human rights laws in the Occupied Palestinian Territory, including in the Gaza Strip since the conflict began there on 13 June. We are calling on both sides to cooperate with the Commission of Inquiry, which must itself be independent and balanced in its approach.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-09-01T08:14:17.9245703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79108/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79108/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-21","Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the legality under international law and the Geneva Conventions of Israel's current actions in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","206816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79109","Scotland Office","false","2014-09-01","<p> </p><p>The Scotland Office estate comprises two leased buildings: one in London and one in Edinburgh. The Scotland Office takes every opportunity to maximise the use of the estate and to reduce running costs.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-09-01T12:45:48.1267678Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79109/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79109/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-07-21","Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if he will review his departmental estate in order to reduce costs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","206694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79110","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2014-09-11","<p>The Commission is currently undertaking work to estimate the cost of implementing and administering a proportionate and accessible scheme for verifying the identity of electors at polling stations. The Commission’s work will include estimating of the potential costs of implementing an electoral identity card scheme, which would be available free of charge to electors in Great Britain who were not in possession of any other form of valid identification.</p><p> </p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2014-09-11T14:49:22.1780365Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79110/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79110/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2014-07-21","Identity Cards","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what estimate the Electoral Commission has made of the cost including postage to (a) the voter and (b) the Electoral Commission, of producing and processing an identity card for the purpose of voting.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","206672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79111","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2014-09-11","<p>The Commission has made no estimate of the cost of Bite the Ballot.</p><p> </p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2014-09-11T13:56:42.0635094Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79111/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79111/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2014-07-21","Electoral Register: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what recent estimate the Electoral Commission has made of the cost of Bite the Ballot.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","206673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79112","Department for Transport","false","2014-09-01","<p> </p><p>The Department for Transport reviews assets and land and property holdings on an ongoing basis. As and when appropriate any land or property holdings deemed surplus are promptly identified and disposed of in accordance with business needs.</p><p> </p><p>This has resulted in reductions in the cost of the department estate and improved space efficiency as reported in the annual State of the Estate Report:</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><strong>2010-11 </strong></td><td><strong>2011-12 </strong></td><td><strong>2012-13 </strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Total cost of the estate</strong></td><td>£166,096,850</td><td>£161,858,767</td><td>£154,653,361</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Occupied space (m2) per FTE</strong></td><td>12.4</td><td>11.9</td><td>10.3</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In addition the Department for Transport has contributed land capable of delivering 3,752 homes to the Public Sector Land Programme, we are continuing to rationalise our estate, delivering cost savings and better value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-09-01T14:02:24.8159474Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79112/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79112/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-07-21","Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will review his departmental estate in order to reduce costs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","206695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79113","Department for Transport","false","2014-09-02","<p> </p><p>The Secretary of State is seeking powers through the Hybrid Bill to construct the HS2 scheme as set out in that Bill. This does not include a new station adjacent to Curzon Street as proposed.　There are a range of potential infrastructure schemes, such as new stations, which could further increase connections for the travelling public above and beyond the scheme set out in the Bill. The Department is not evaluating the case for such proposals and will therefore not undertake a study on a new station to serve Curzon Street.　The Department will continue to work with local authorities who are taking the lead in identifying and evaluating options for wider connectivity that will extend the benefits offered by HS2.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-09-02T14:21:04.329727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79113/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79113/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-07-21","Railways: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will initiate a study into adding a halt on the Lichfield Trent Valley to Redditch cross-city line at Curzon Street in Birmingham adjacent to the proposed Birmingham High Speed 2 (HS2) station to enhance connectivity with HS2 and with Birmingham City University and Millennium Point; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","206679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79114","Department for Transport","false","2014-09-01","<p> </p><p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) does not hold this information for individual parliamentary constituencies or UK regions. Between January 2011 and June 2014, there were 115,829 prosecutions throughout the UK for using or keeping an untaxed vehicle on the public road.</p><p> </p><p>Prosecutions for the offence of keeping an uninsured vehicle began in November 2011. Up until the end of June 2014, 68,598 prosecutions for this offence had been taken forward across Great Britain.</p><p> </p><p>The DVLA does not hold figures about prosecutions where the vehicle was both untaxed and uninsured.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-09-01T13:55:42.6050032Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79114/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79114/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-07-21","Driving Offences: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many prosecutions the DVLA has brought for (a) possessing and (b) driving an uninsured and untaxed vehicle in (i) Llanelli constituency, (ii) Wales and (iii) the UK since 2011.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","206708"
